observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Accountant:
Review the records and determine the estimated useful lives of the infrastructure assets and other assets not provided with depreciation;
Compute the depreciation based on the estimated remaining useful lives of the assets;
Take up prior years’ depreciation as Prior Years’ Adjustment to be closed to the Government Equity account while the current year’s depreciation be recorded as expense; and
Adhere to the accounting and reporting guidelines on local roads prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated                November 25, 2015 considering that a major portion of the undepreciated Infrastructure Assets of the City as of year-end pertains to Road Networks.

We recommend that management consider in the guidelines of the Livelihood Assistance Program, the following requirements of essential documentation and information, and procedures relevant to the screening of beneficiaries to protect the interest of the government, to wit:

provision on the income level of the applicant to be granted the loan;
submission of a project proposal/ feasibility study duly supported with the projected income within the loan paying period or the financial reports for the years it is projected to be in operation;
assessment by  an Evaluation Committee who will study and evaluate the applicant’s proposal and eligibility, and recommend its approval or disapproval to the City Mayor;
provision for the training and technical assistance by the LGU to the grantee;
provision for limitations on grants to applicants who still have unpaid balances of loans previously granted by the city; and
inclusion in the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA), Item No. 8 in the guidelines which states that “Xxx. The loaner shall submit report on Return of Investment, six (6) months after the release of the loan.”
